{"type":"message","id":"bb6ccf6b","parentId":"08b199aa","timestamp":"2026-03-20T09:50:19.587Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_88cdf293-6402-4cf7-bb4c-2989c86a4fe3","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"total 20\ndrwxrwxr-x  2 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 4096 Mar 20 00:44 .\ndrwxrwxr-x 10 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 4096 Mar 19 10:56 ..\n-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 7739 Mar 19 10:54 archived_draft_001_v1_ai.md\n-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 2180 Mar 20 00:44 posted_draft_001.md"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":18,"aggregated":"total 20\ndrwxrwxr-x  2 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 4096 Mar 20 00:44 .\ndrwxrwxr-x 10 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 4096 Mar 19 10:56 ..\n-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 7739 Mar 19 10:54 archived_draft_001_v1_ai.md\n-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 2180 Mar 20 00:44 posted_draft_001.md","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774000219585}}
{"type":"message","id":"97d31cc0","parentId":"bb6ccf6b","timestamp":"2026-03-20T09:50:21.629Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_47f079d0-c94f-4be9-a85a-e519c7fa2976","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/rag/drafts/posted_draft_001.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.5:cloud","usage":{"input":37077,"output":70,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":37147,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1774000221629}}
{"type":"message","id":"19620399","parentId":"97d31cc0","timestamp":"2026-03-20T09:50:21.652Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_47f079d0-c94f-4be9-a85a-e519c7fa2976","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nplatform: LinkedIn\nauthor: Nava Healthcare Recruitment\nurl: https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7440527552143597568\ndate: 2026-03-19\nstatus: posted\ntype: post-first\nimage: none (CTA links to article)\n\n𝗪𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗶𝗳 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗿𝗲𝗰𝗿𝘂𝗶𝘁𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗳𝗲𝗲 𝘄𝗮𝘀 𝘀𝗽𝗿𝗲𝗮𝗱 𝗼𝘃𝗲𝗿 𝟭𝟮 𝘄𝗲𝗲𝗸𝘀? For every week your new hire stays, your agency gets 8–10% more of the full fee. They hit 100% at week 12.\n\nSounds 𝘣𝘦𝘵𝘵𝘦𝘳, right?\n\nYour agency would actually care about compatibility. They'd follow up and worry if someone might quit at week 3 because that's money left on the table.\n\nBut tricks are for kids, and here's why this dream will never work in practice.\n\n𝗔𝗱𝗺𝗻𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗿𝗮𝘁𝗶𝘃𝗲𝗹𝘆: Spreading payments over 12 weeks is a nightmare for your HR department. Tracking, invoicing, and reconciliation; it multiplies the workload.\n\n𝗔𝗴𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗲𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝗮 𝗳𝗮𝗶𝗿 𝗮𝗿𝗴𝘂𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁: They've done the sourcing, vetting, presenting, and placing. They've found your candidate and got them through the door. Why wait 3 months to get paid in full?\n\nRegardless, this model is objectively better for healthcare facilities, yet it's impractical. No agency would jeopardize its revenue to make it even more unpredictable.\n\nAt Nava, we don't stretch the fee over 12 weeks. We put our money where our mouth is. 𝗭𝗲𝗿𝗼 𝘂𝗽𝗳𝗿𝗼𝗻𝘁 𝗰𝗼𝘀𝘁𝘀. We get paid only when your hire proves themselves.\n\nWe get it. As former healthcare executives, we were frustrated each time an early resignation cost us time and money. We built Nava around a different philosophy — not how we charge, but how we align.\n\n𝘛𝘩𝘢𝘵'𝘴 𝘫𝘶𝘴𝘵 𝘥𝘰𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘁𝘩𝘪𝘯𝘨𝘴 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗹𝘆.\n\nWe wrote about what actually to look for in a medical recruiting agency and why we built Nava around a different philosophy: 👉 https://navahc.com/how-to-find-the-best-medical-recruiting-agencies/\n---\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774000221649}}
{"type":"message","id":"b8a1ccaa","parentId":"19620399","timestamp":"2026-03-20T09:50:28.554Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_1c1fa491-8a31-4c39-8d24-5238d46afb2d","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 - <<'PY'\nimport json\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\n# Search all sessions from March 19 for X/twitter version of the post\nsession_dir = Path.home() / \".openclaw/agents/main/sessions\"\nfiles = [\n    \"3cc6ca82-1ca8-42f1-aecf-28dc54eb6e99.jsonl\",\n    \"f10748f9-ff06-4fe4-a081-a25c9806933d.jsonl\",\n    \"961b6909-77d2-4bc3-b0aa-2d63fc94a2fc.jsonl\",\n    \"459b1912-afd9-4638-8e24-1aedaf62ac70.jsonl\",\n    \"81925542-1588-4cfc-8284-8adba71eb832.jsonl\",\n    \"29ab19df-1439-441e-82a5-6296d22fadf7.jsonl\",\n]\n\nfor fname in files:\n    with open(session_dir / fname) as f:\n        for line in f:\n            d = json.loads(line)\n            if d.get(\"type\") == \"message\":\n                content = d.get(\"message\", {}).get(\"content\", [])\n                if isinstance(content, list):\n                    text = \"\".join([c.get(\"text\", \"\") for c in content if c.get(\"type\") == \"text\"])\n                else:\n                    text = content\n                # Look for X tweet or twitter content\n                if \"tweet\" in text.lower() or (\"x \" in text.lower() and len(text) < 500):\n                    role = d.get(\"message\", {}).get(\"role\", \"?\")\n                    print(f\"[{fname[:8]}... {role}]: {text}\")\n                    print(\"---\")\nPY"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.5:cloud","usage":{"input":37799,"output":454,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":38253,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1774000228553}}
{"type":"message","id":"4cbac1a5","parentId":"b8a1ccaa","timestamp":"2026-03-20T09:50:28.667Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_1c1fa491-8a31-4c39-8d24-5238d46afb2d","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[3cc6ca82... toolResult]: total 52\ndrwxrwxr-x 2 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv  4096 Mar 18 13:45 .\ndrwxr-xr-x 9 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv  4096 Mar 18 21:21 ..\n-rw-rw-r-- 1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv   303 Mar 10 02:19 2026-03-10.md\n-rw-rw-r-- 1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 22680 Mar 19 05:30 2026-03-17.md\n-rw-rw-r-- 1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv  4157 Mar 18 21:25 2026-03-18.md\n-rw-rw-r-- 1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv   703 Mar 10 03:28 contacts.md\n-rw-rw-r-- 1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv  1010 Mar 10 03:25 ncami.md\n---\n[3cc6ca82... user]: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Thu 2026-03-19 10:06 GMT+2] I think you defaulted back to OpenAI overnight and now those tokens are finished. I will be using Minimax and Nemotron going forward. But I need to know which is best. Both are cloud models. Can you help me?\n---\n[3cc6ca82... assistant]: **Benchmark results:**\n\n| Model | Time | Output Tokens | Notes |\n|-------|------|---------------|-------|\n| **Minimax** | 4.4s | 277 | Shows internal thinking in output |\n| **Nemotron** | 3.8s | 66 | Cleaner, more concise |\n\n**Quick take:**\n- **Nemotron** is faster (~15% quicker) and ~4x more token-efficient\n- **Minimax** shows its reasoning/thinking — useful for debugging, but burns more tokens\n\nWant me to test something more complex (coding, writing) to see how they compare?\n---\n[3cc6ca82... user]: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Thu 2026-03-19 10:08 GMT+2] Let's stick to Minimax for now. However, can you check on the internet which model is better, or if there are any other models available on Ollama that I should be considering instead of this?\n---\n[3cc6ca82... toolResult]: # Task 2 — Nava Content Engine Spec (Final Draft v1)\n\nDate: 2026-03-18\nOwner: Dawn\nStatus: Draft ready for user review\n\n## 1) Objective\nCreate a production-safe content engine for Nava that:\n- Generates ideas and drafts only within Nava’s staffing/recruiting domain\n- Grounds claims in source evidence from approved corpus/docs\n- Produces channel-ready outputs (LinkedIn + X mandatory; FB optional)\n- Enforces human review before any publish action\n\n## 2) Non-Negotiable Guardrails\n1. Domain gate: only staffing/recruiting content tied to Nava taxonomy\n2. Evidence gate: claims must map to source URLs or internal doc citations\n3. Confidence gate: if evidence is weak, output `insufficient support`\n4. Publish gate: no autonomous publishing; explicit human approval required\n5. Format gate: channel templates must be followed exactly\n\n## 3) Inputs\n- Website corpus (crawl + clean text + synthesis)\n- Internal docs (`docs/`, `docs/converted/`)\n- RAG index outputs (`rag/index/*`)\n- Existing guardrails config (`rag/config/content_guardrails.yaml`)\n\n## 4) Content Taxonomy (enforced)\nEach idea/draft must tag:\n- Primary topic\n- Audience (candidate / employer / operator)\n- Funnel stage (awareness / consideration / conversion)\n- Evidence set (source ids/urls)\n- Risk level (low/med/high claim sensitivity)\n\nIf taxonomy tag cannot be assigned confidently -> reject item.\n\n## 5) Pipeline\n## Stage A — Idea Generation\nInput: corpus gaps + recent themes\nOutput: structured idea cards with:\n- headline\n- thesis\n- target audience\n- taxonomy tags\n- required evidence checklist\n\n## Stage B — Evidence Binding\nFor each idea:\n- Run retrieval\n- Attach top supporting snippets + URLs\n- Mark unsupported lines\n\nPass criteria: each major claim has at least one explicit source.\n\n## Stage C — Drafting\nGenerate:\n- LinkedIn draft (primary)\n- X derivative (1–3 tweets)\n- Optional FB adaptation only when fit is high\n\nRules:\n- Executive/operator tone\n- Compressed sentences, natural short paragraphs\n- Caption complements image (does not restate)\n\n## Stage D — Validation\nAutomated checks:\n- Domain classifier pass/fail\n- Evidence coverage score\n- Style constraints\n- Banned/off-domain phrase detection\n\nIf fail -> return diagnostics + regenerate.\n\n## Stage E — Human Review Pack\nBundle per post:\n- Final draft(s)\n- Claim-to-source map\n- Risk notes\n- Suggested image direction\n\nNo queue/publish unless approved.\n\n## 6) Output Schemas\n## 6.1 Idea Card\n- id\n- title\n- one_line_angle\n- audience\n- taxonomy_tags[]\n- evidence_requirements[]\n- rejection_reason (nullable)\n\n## 6.2 Draft Pack\n- draft_id\n- channel (linkedin|x|fb)\n- copy\n- claims[]\n- sources[]\n- confidence_score\n- review_status (needs_review|approved|rejected)\n\n## 7) Quality Targets\n- 100% taxonomy-tagged ideas\n- 100% major claims source-linked\n- <5% off-domain rejects after prompt tuning\n- Zero publish without human approval\n\n## 8) Model Routing (current agreed posture)\n- Primary execution: Minimax cloud in OpenClaw session\n- Keep prompts short/structured to reduce context bloat\n- Use strict templates for schema outputs\n\n## 9) Next Deliverables (Task 3+ handoff)\n1. Ingestion update flow for new articles (Task 3)\n2. Corpus-derived idea bank (Task 4)\n3. Queue-ready drafts for LinkedIn/X/FB (Task 5)\n4. Image refinement workflow (Task 6)\n5. Final queue pack + ordering (Task 7)\n\n## 10) Open Decisions for Tiny\n1. Confirm final taxonomy labels (if any rename needed)\n2. Set confidence score threshold for `insufficient support`\n3. Confirm FB inclusion rule (always optional vs conditional)\n4. Confirm claim granularity for source mapping (line-by-line vs grouped)\n\n---\n[3cc6ca82... assistant]: Makes total sense. You need:\n1. **Chat/brain** → Minimax (you're using)\n2. **Vision** → to analyze screenshots/images and help craft prompts for image generation\n\nFrom what I saw in Ollama's library, cloud vision models include:\n- `gemma3:4b` / `gemma3:12b` / `gemma3:27b` (Google's latest, vision + cloud)\n- `qwen3-vl:235b` (Alibaba, large vision)\n\nLet me continue with Task 3 and note the vision model as a parallel need:\n---\n[3cc6ca82... assistant]: Schema mismatch. Let me fix the ingest script to match the existing chunk format:\n---\n[3cc6ca82... toolResult]: {\"model\":\"minimax-m2.7\",\"created_at\":\"2026-03-19T08:48:42.820193931Z\",\"response\":\"Hello! It's great to meet you.\",\"thinking\":\"The user wants the assistant to say hello in one sentence. This is straightforward. The user says \\\"Hi, testing Minimax 2.7. Say hello in 1 sentence.\\\"\\n\\nThe answer: \\\"Hello! It's great to meet you.\\\"\\n\\nMake sure it's one sentence. Let's comply.\",\"done\":true,\"done_reason\":\"stop\",\"total_duration\":9885169706,\"prompt_eval_count\":58,\"eval_count\":70}\n---\n[3cc6ca82... assistant]: **Done:**\n\n- ✅ Tested Minimax 2.7 cloud (working)\n- ✅ Backed up config to `TinyBackUp/openclaw-20260319-*.json`\n- ✅ Updated config:\n  - **Primary:** `minimax-m2.7:cloud`\n  - **Fallbacks:** `minimax-m2.5:cloud` → `nemotron-3-super:cloud`\n- ✅ Updated memory\n\n**To apply:**\n\n```bash\nopenclaw gateway restart\n```\n\nAfter restart, I'll continue autonomously with Tasks 4–7. Any questions before you restart?\n---\n[3cc6ca82... assistant]: Yes, I'm here! ✅ \n\nMinimax 2.7 is now live. Ready to continue with Tasks 4–7 autonomously. What would you like me to tackle next?\n---\n[f10748f9... user]: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Thu 2026-03-19 11:51 GMT+2] You, know what, add this to a problem I need to fix later.\n---\n[f10748f9... toolResult]: error: missing required argument 'query'\n\nUsage: clawhub search [options] <query...>\n\nVector search skills\n\nArguments:\n  query        Query string\n\nOptions:\n  --limit <n>  Max results\n  -h, --help   display help for command\n---\n[f10748f9... toolResult]: iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAB4AAAAMkCAIAAADWAqp6AAABKGlDQ1BfAAB4nJWQzS4DYRSGH01F\nNKxYWJCMnQ2qjZbEglY1dtIiLavptJ2IdkymIyxcgmsQsbGUiEtwAUJiZeESxMLaOzNkmkgXzpcz\n58k77/dzDiSmUCTT0HV8r1IuGLX6gTHyzpBWGKbVcxkccn---\n/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/media/browser/5e4dbfd4-02dc-4df1-9246-7b72b5c6ace4.png: PNG image data, 1920 x 804, 8-bit/color RGB, non-interlaced\n---\n[f10748f9... assistant]: It's working perfectly. Let me update memory and fix the config mismatch:\n\n---\n[f10748f9... assistant]: The relay works. Quick status:\n\n✅ **`chrome-relay` is active and functional** — screenshot confirmed, navigation confirmed, page reading confirmed (1920×804 = real desktop browser)\n\n⚠️ **Config mismatch** — your `openclaw.json` has `defaultProfile: \"chrome\"` but that profile doesn't exist. Every browser command fails silently unless you pass `--browser-profile chrome-relay`. I can fix this in one line when you're ready.\n\n---\n\nNow let me update memory with today's research findings:\n\n---\n[f10748f9... assistant]: Good. Now fix the config and test:\n\n---\n[f10748f9... user]: Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Thu 2026-03-19 13:15 GMT+2] Hold on, this may be because you are already connected to my personal profile. It might be the case that you can only control 1 profile at a time. (This is not a train smash and is not urgent but I might want to fix it in the future).\n---\n[f10748f9... toolResult]: # Task 5 — Queue-Ready Drafts\n## Generated: 2026-03-19 | Status: Ready for Tiny Review\n\n---\n\n## DRAFT 001 — Cost Ontology\n**Idea:** \"What Most Healthcare Leaders Get Wrong About Staffing Costs\"\n**Channel:** LinkedIn (primary)\n**Funnel:** Consideration → Decision\n**Risk Level:** Medium\n\n### LinkedIn Draft\n\n---\n\n**Most healthcare leaders are looking at staffing costs wrong.**\n\nThey see the agency fee. They compare it to bill rates. They negotiate margins.\n\nBut that's not the real cost of their staffing model.\n\nThe real cost of reactive healthcare staffing has three layers:\n\n**1. Vacancy cost**\nEvery unfilled shift carries hidden weight — overtime, burned-out permanent staff, care quality risk. A single open RN position can cost $50K–$120K per year when you factor in temporary laborpremiums and the downstream impact on team morale and patient outcomes.\n\n**2. Turnover cost**\nThe average RN turnover costs $40K–$65K. But in healthcare, that's not just a number — it's your colleagues, your unit culture, your patient continuity. Most facilities underestimate how much turnover compounds when you're constantly filling gaps with strangers.\n\n**3. Compliance risk**\nUnderstaffing triggers CMS violations. Credentialing gaps create liability exposure. The cost of a survey failure or a patient incident from being short-staffed is incalculable — in both financial and reputational terms.\n\n**The question isn't: \"Is the agency too expensive?\"**\n\n**The question is: \"What's the full cost of the model we're running?\"**\n\nIf your staffing partner can't answer that question — or doesn't want to — that's your signal.\n\n---\n\n**#HealthcareStaffing #HealthcareLeadership #StaffingStrategy #HealthcareOperations #ReactiveHiring**\n\n---\n\n### X Derivative (3 tweets)\n\n**Tweet 1:**\nMost healthcare leaders compare agency fees.\nThey should be comparing vacancy cost, turnover cost, and compliance risk.\nThat's the real staffing cost picture. 🧵\n\n**Tweet 2:**\nA single unfilled RN shift:\n→ Overtime premium\n→ Burned permanent staff\n→ Patient safety risk\n→ CMS violation exposure\nThe agency fee is the smallest line item.\n\n**Tweet 3:**\nThe question isn't \"is our staffing partner too expensive?\"\nIt's \"what's the full cost of our current model?\"\nIf they can't answer — that's your signal.\n\n---\n\n**Suggested Image Direction:**\nInfographic — \"The Staffing Cost Iceberg\" — agency fee visible above waterline, vacancy + turnover + compliance below. Striking visual, one bold stat buried in the bottom third.\n\n---\n\n## DRAFT 002 — LTC/SNF/CHC Targeting\n**Idea:** \"Why Your LTC Facility Keeps Running Short (And What Actually Works)\"\n**Channel:** LinkedIn (primary)\n**Funnel:** Awareness → Consideration\n**Risk Level:** Low\n\n### LinkedIn Draft\n\n---\n\n**Long-term care facilities have a staffing problem that hospitals don't.**\n\nIn acute care, a gap is visible and urgent — code blues, overcapacity, immediate patient risk.\n\nIn LTC, the problem is quieter. It hides in declining survey scores. In staff who've been doing double shifts for six months. In the CNA who's now managing twice the residents she was hired for.\n\n**The LTC staffing challenge is structural, not cyclical.**\n\nHospitals can pull from a broader labor pool. LTC requires people willing to work with geriatric populations — a specific calling, a specific skill set, a specific tolerance for the pace of long-term care.\n\n**What's actually driving the shortage in your building?**\n\n- **Referral pipeline collapse** — when one good CNAs leaves, the people who would've referred their network are gone too\n- **Perception gap** — LTC careers are undervalued in the broader nursing community, making recruitment harder\n- **Relationship deficit** — facilities that treat staffing like procurement (lowest bid, most bodies) can't retain the people who make care actually work\n\n**The LTC facilities that are winning on staffing?**\n\nThey're not outbidding hospitals. They're not running job boards on endless loops.\n\nThey're building relational staffing models — a stable core, a trusted partner network, a culture that keeps the people they have.\n\n---\n\n**#LTCStaffing #SkilledNursing #HealthcareStaffing #HealthcareLeadership #StaffingStrategy**\n\n---\n\n### X Derivative (2 tweets)\n\n**Tweet 1:**\nLTC staffing isn't a hospital problem with extra steps.\nThe challenge is structural:\n— Geriatric-specific skills\n— Relationship-based retention\n— Pipeline collapse compounds\nMost facilities treat it like procurement. It isn't.\n\n**Tweet 2:**\nThe LTC facilities winning on staffing?\nNot the ones with the biggest job board budget.\nThey're running relational models — stable core, trusted partner, culture that keeps good people.\n\n---\n\n**Suggested Image Direction:**\nPhoto of actual LTC facility environment (warm, dignified) vs stock hospital imagery — contrast relational care setting with clinical sterotype. Caption: \"This is where care happens.\"\n\n---\n\n## DRAFT 011 — Relationship-First Hiring (Evergreen)\n**Idea:** \"Relationship > Transaction — The Staffing Model That Actually Works\"\n**Channel:** LinkedIn + X + FB\n**Funnel:** Awareness\n**Risk Level:** Low\n\n### LinkedIn Draft\n\n---\n\n**Healthcare staffing has a transaction problem.**\n\nPost a job. Get resumes. Fill the shift. Move on.\n\nIt's fast. It's scalable. It looks efficient on a spreadsheet.\n\nAnd it's failing your patients, your permanent staff, and your outcomes.\n\n**Transactional staffing treats people like interchangeable units of labor.**\n\nWhen you fill a shift with whoever's available, you get whoever's available — not whoever fits your culture, your patient population, your team dynamics, your clinical reality.\n\n**Relational staffing is different.**\n\nIt starts with understanding: your facility's specific needs, your unit's clinical priorities, your team's working style, your patient population's acuity level.\n\nThen it sources, vets, and places people who actually fit — not just people who are available.\n\n**The difference shows up in retention.**\n\nRelational placement isn't just about filling today's shift. It's about building a staffing model that compounds over time — where the right people stay, your permanent staff stop carrying impossible loads, and patient care actually reflects your standards.\n\n**The healthcare facilities getting this right aren't running bigger job boards.**\n\nThey're running different models.\n\n---\n\n**#HealthcareStaffing #StaffingStrategy #HealthcareLeadership #RelationalStaffing #TalentAcquisition**\n\n---\n\n### X Derivative (2 tweets)\n\n**Tweet 1:**\nHealthcare staffing is broken because most facilities are running a transaction, not a relationship.\nPost → Fill → Move on.\nIt works on a spreadsheet. It's failing your patients.\n\n**Tweet 2:**\nRelational staffing:\n→ Starts with understanding your facility, not filling a slot\n→ Compounds over time (retention > placement)\n→ Reduces burden on permanent staff\n→ Actually fixes the problem\nMost facilities aren't running this model.\n\n---\n\n**Suggested Image Direction:**\nTwo hands meeting — symbolic of relationship/trust. Warm, professional, human. Not clinical. Caption: \"The handshake that changes your staffing model.\"\n\n---\n\n## Review Pack Summary\n\n| Draft | Channel | Risk | Evidence Status | Image Direction |\n|-------|---------|------|-----------------|-----------------|\n| 001 — Cost Ontology | LinkedIn + X | Medium | Needs data sourcing | Iceberg infographic |\n| 002 — LTC Targeting | LinkedIn + X | Low | Needs LTC-specific stats | LTC environment photo |\n| 011 — Relationship-First | LinkedIn + X + FB | Low | Grounded in synthesis | Human connection photo |\n\n---\n\n**Next: Tiny approves → image prompts generated → Task 6 (image refinement)**\n---\n[f10748f9... assistant]: I know — the session is full at 204800 tokens (869KB of history). I can't respond when context is maxed.\n\nQuick fix — run this in WSL:\n\n```bash\n/compact\n```\n\nThat forces OpenClaw to summarise older history and free up context. Then I'll be back.\n\nOr if that do