eaks the relay\n2. **To use chrome-relay**: always pass `--browser-profile chrome-relay`\n3. **If errors occur**: Check `openclaw browser profiles` — if you see profiles but get errors, restart gateway\n\n### Working command\n```bash\nopenclaw browser --browser-profile chrome-relay screenshot\nopenclaw browser --browser-profile chrome-relay navigate <url>\n```\n\n### Current config state (working)\n- `defaultProfile`: REMOVED (key fix)\n- `profiles.openclaw`: port 18800 (WSL Chrome, not used)\n- `relayBindHost`: 0.0.0.0 (allows external connections)\n\n### Backup files\n- ~/TinyBackUp/20260319/openclaw.json.154346 — current working config\n- ~/TinyBackUp/20260319/MEMORY.md.154348 — current memory\n\n## Nava LinkedIn Posts (2026-03-19)\n\nFound 3 published posts on company page (Aug-Oct 2025):\n- **Oct 3, 2025**: \"The ROI of Investing in Employee Wellness: Why Companies Are Putting Health First\" — 111 reactions, 9 comments\n- **Sep 5, 2025**: \"The Real Cost of Employee Turnover: Why Retention is the New Recruitment\" — 52 reactions, 4 comments\n- **Aug 8, 2025**: \"The Employee Benefit Your Workforce Actually Wants\" — 42 reactions, 4 comments\n\nAdmin URL: https://www.linkedin.com/company/67170741/admin/page-posts/published/\n\n### LinkedIn Page IDs\n- Nava Healthcare (company): 67170741 (not the same as nava-healthcare slug)\n\n### Recent LinkedIn Posts Content (from 2025-03)\n\n**5 days ago - \"The False Finish Line\"**\n- Topic: Most healthcare recruiting teams think the race is over the moment the offer is accepted. In reality, that's a false finish line.\n- Key message: Stay engaged with candidate between offer acceptance and Day 60\n- Nava differentiator: No upfront costs, fees only when confident in placement\n\n**2 weeks ago (Edited) - \"The Universal License Fallacy\"**\n- Topic: A clinical license is a measure of minimum competency, not a predictor of professional success\n- Key message: Don't hire the CV, hire the person behind the qualifications\n- Key concept: Cultural concordance - understanding pace of unit, temperament of leadership, patient demographics\n- Differentiation: Humans with compassionate focus, not AI sifting through CVs\n\n**3 weeks ago - \"The 90-Day Waiting Period\"**\n- Topic: 90-day healthcare benefits waiting period universally hated by clinical candidates\n- Key message: For elite talent (1%), justify strategic exception to drop the red tape\n- Story: A talented DON turned down an offer due to 90-day waiting period; Nava got it reduced to 30 days\n\n**~2 weeks ago - \"The Cost of Vacancies\"**\n- Topic: Break down of the \"backfill spiral\" - what a single vacancy costs a facility\n- Key metrics: Up to $X/day for RN vacancy, 50%+ labor cost inflation from overtime/agency\n\n**~2 weeks ago - \"The Brand Gap\"**\n- Topic: It takes 6 months/millions to approve hospital rebranding, 6 minutes to destroy it\n- Key concept: Employer Brand = leading indicator of Patient Brand\n- Message: Marketing makes the promise, clinical culture delivers it\n\n**Earlier posts (Aug-Oct 2025)** - See full text captured separately\n\n---\n[29ab19df... assistant]: Honestly? I don't see evidence that compaction is actually working. The issue keeps recurring:\n\n- **Yesterday**: Context overflow on Minimax (651 tokens over)\n- **Today**: Another overflow (142-228 tokens over)\n\nThe context just grows until it hits the limit, then we reset. That's not compaction — that's collapse.\n\nLet me check if OpenClaw has a compaction feature we should be using:\n---\n[29ab19df... toolResult]: total 16\ndrwxrwxr-x  2 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 4096 Mar 19 10:54 .\ndrwxrwxr-x 10 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 4096 Mar 19 10:56 ..\n-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv 7739 Mar 19 10:54 queue_draft_001.md\n---\n[29ab19df... toolResult]: # Task 5 — Queue-Ready Drafts\n## Generated: 2026-03-19 | Status: Ready for Tiny Review\n\n---\n\n## DRAFT 001 — Cost Ontology\n**Idea:** \"What Most Healthcare Leaders Get Wrong About Staffing Costs\"\n**Channel:** LinkedIn (primary)\n**Funnel:** Consideration → Decision\n**Risk Level:** Medium\n\n### LinkedIn Draft\n\n---\n\n**Most healthcare leaders are looking at staffing costs wrong.**\n\nThey see the agency fee. They compare it to bill rates. They negotiate margins.\n\nBut that's not the real cost of their staffing model.\n\nThe real cost of reactive healthcare staffing has three layers:\n\n**1. Vacancy cost**\nEvery unfilled shift carries hidden weight — overtime, burned-out permanent staff, care quality risk. A single open RN position can cost $50K–$120K per year when you factor in temporary laborpremiums and the downstream impact on team morale and patient outcomes.\n\n**2. Turnover cost**\nThe average RN turnover costs $40K–$65K. But in healthcare, that's not just a number — it's your colleagues, your unit culture, your patient continuity. Most facilities underestimate how much turnover compounds when you're constantly filling gaps with strangers.\n\n**3. Compliance risk**\nUnderstaffing triggers CMS violations. Credentialing gaps create liability exposure. The cost of a survey failure or a patient incident from being short-staffed is incalculable — in both financial and reputational terms.\n\n**The question isn't: \"Is the agency too expensive?\"**\n\n**The question is: \"What's the full cost of the model we're running?\"**\n\nIf your staffing partner can't answer that question — or doesn't want to — that's your signal.\n\n---\n\n**#HealthcareStaffing #HealthcareLeadership #StaffingStrategy #HealthcareOperations #ReactiveHiring**\n\n---\n\n### X Derivative (3 tweets)\n\n**Tweet 1:**\nMost healthcare leaders compare agency fees.\nThey should be comparing vacancy cost, turnover cost, and compliance risk.\nThat's the real staffing cost picture. 🧵\n\n**Tweet 2:**\nA single unfilled RN shift:\n→ Overtime premium\n→ Burned permanent staff\n→ Patient safety risk\n→ CMS violation exposure\nThe agency fee is the smallest line item.\n\n**Tweet 3:**\nThe question isn't \"is our staffing partner too expensive?\"\nIt's \"what's the full cost of our current model?\"\nIf they can't answer — that's your signal.\n\n---\n\n**Suggested Image Direction:**\nInfographic — \"The Staffing Cost Iceberg\" — agency fee visible above waterline, vacancy + turnover + compliance below. Striking visual, one bold stat buried in the bottom third.\n\n---\n\n## DRAFT 002 — LTC/SNF/CHC Targeting\n**Idea:** \"Why Your LTC Facility Keeps Running Short (And What Actually Works)\"\n**Channel:** LinkedIn (primary)\n**Funnel:** Awareness → Consideration\n**Risk Level:** Low\n\n### LinkedIn Draft\n\n---\n\n**Long-term care facilities have a staffing problem that hospitals don't.**\n\nIn acute care, a gap is visible and urgent — code blues, overcapacity, immediate patient risk.\n\nIn LTC, the problem is quieter. It hides in declining survey scores. In staff who've been doing double shifts for six months. In the CNA who's now managing twice the residents she was hired for.\n\n**The LTC staffing challenge is structural, not cyclical.**\n\nHospitals can pull from a broader labor pool. LTC requires people willing to work with geriatric populations — a specific calling, a specific skill set, a specific tolerance for the pace of long-term care.\n\n**What's actually driving the shortage in your building?**\n\n- **Referral pipeline collapse** — when one good CNAs leaves, the people who would've referred their network are gone too\n- **Perception gap** — LTC careers are undervalued in the broader nursing community, making recruitment harder\n- **Relationship deficit** — facilities that treat staffing like procurement (lowest bid, most bodies) can't retain the people who make care actually work\n\n**The LTC facilities that are winning on staffing?**\n\nThey're not outbidding hospitals. They're not running job boards on endless loops.\n\nThey're building relational staffing models — a stable core, a trusted partner network, a culture that keeps the people they have.\n\n---\n\n**#LTCStaffing #SkilledNursing #HealthcareStaffing #HealthcareLeadership #StaffingStrategy**\n\n---\n\n### X Derivative (2 tweets)\n\n**Tweet 1:**\nLTC staffing isn't a hospital problem with extra steps.\nThe challenge is structural:\n— Geriatric-specific skills\n— Relationship-based retention\n— Pipeline collapse compounds\nMost facilities treat it like procurement. It isn't.\n\n**Tweet 2:**\nThe LTC facilities winning on staffing?\nNot the ones with the biggest job board budget.\nThey're running relational models — stable core, trusted partner, culture that keeps good people.\n\n---\n\n**Suggested Image Direction:**\nPhoto of actual LTC facility environment (warm, dignified) vs stock hospital imagery — contrast relational care setting with clinical sterotype. Caption: \"This is where care happens.\"\n\n---\n\n## DRAFT 011 — Relationship-First Hiring (Evergreen)\n**Idea:** \"Relationship > Transaction — The Staffing Model That Actually Works\"\n**Channel:** LinkedIn + X + FB\n**Funnel:** Awareness\n**Risk Level:** Low\n\n### LinkedIn Draft\n\n---\n\n**Healthcare staffing has a transaction problem.**\n\nPost a job. Get resumes. Fill the shift. Move on.\n\nIt's fast. It's scalable. It looks efficient on a spreadsheet.\n\nAnd it's failing your patients, your permanent staff, and your outcomes.\n\n**Transactional staffing treats people like interchangeable units of labor.**\n\nWhen you fill a shift with whoever's available, you get whoever's available — not whoever fits your culture, your patient population, your team dynamics, your clinical reality.\n\n**Relational staffing is different.**\n\nIt starts with understanding: your facility's specific needs, your unit's clinical priorities, your team's working style, your patient population's acuity level.\n\nThen it sources, vets, and places people who actually fit — not just people who are available.\n\n**The difference shows up in retention.**\n\nRelational placement isn't just about filling today's shift. It's about building a staffing model that compounds over time — where the right people stay, your permanent staff stop carrying impossible loads, and patient care actually reflects your standards.\n\n**The healthcare facilities getting this right aren't running bigger job boards.**\n\nThey're running different models.\n\n---\n\n**#HealthcareStaffing #StaffingStrategy #HealthcareLeadership #RelationalStaffing #TalentAcquisition**\n\n---\n\n### X Derivative (2 tweets)\n\n**Tweet 1:**\nHealthcare staffing is broken because most facilities are running a transaction, not a relationship.\nPost → Fill → Move on.\nIt works on a spreadsheet. It's failing your patients.\n\n**Tweet 2:**\nRelational staffing:\n→ Starts with understanding your facility, not filling a slot\n→ Compounds over time (retention > placement)\n→ Reduces burden on permanent staff\n→ Actually fixes the problem\nMost facilities aren't running this model.\n\n---\n\n**Suggested Image Direction:**\nTwo hands meeting — symbolic of relationship/trust. Warm, professional, human. Not clinical. Caption: \"The handshake that changes your staffing model.\"\n\n---\n\n## Review Pack Summary\n\n| Draft | Channel | Risk | Evidence Status | Image Direction |\n|-------|---------|------|-----------------|-----------------|\n| 001 — Cost Ontology | LinkedIn + X | Medium | Needs data sourcing | Iceberg infographic |\n| 002 — LTC Targeting | LinkedIn + X | Low | Needs LTC-specific stats | LTC environment photo |\n| 011 — Relationship-First | LinkedIn + X + FB | Low | Grounded in synthesis | Human connection photo |\n\n---\n\n**Next: Tiny approves → image prompts generated → Task 6 (image refinement)**\n\n---\n[29ab19df... toolResult]: \n# Nava Healthcare Content Execution Guide\n### LinkedIn + X Operating Manual for Custom GPT\n\n---\n\n# 1. Purpose of this Document\n\nThis document teaches a GPT how to actually execute Nava content, not just understand the strategy.\n\nThe first markdown defines context and mission.\nThis markdown defines how posts are written, discussed, and translated across platforms.\n\nThe goal is to replicate the user's real workflow and editorial voice as closely as possible.\n\n---\n\n# 2. Core Execution Workflow\n\n## Step 1 — Concept Discussion\n\nNo drafting yet.\n\nThe GPT and user discuss:\n- the core insight\n- the angle\n- the strategic point\n- how the idea differs from previously published content\n\nConcepts should be pressure-tested through discussion.\n\nThe GPT should:\n- challenge weak framing\n- propose stronger angles\n- avoid agreeability\n\nUser prefers collaborative debate rather than passive agreement.\n\n---\n\n## Step 2 — Decide Image-first or Post-first\n\nTwo possible workflows:\n\n### Image First\n1. Develop image concept\n2. Generate visual\n3. Write caption/post interpreting the image\n\n### Post First\n1. Draft post\n2. Design visual metaphor to complement it\n\nImportant rule:\n\nThe post must not simply describe the image.\n\nImage = metaphor  \nPost = interpretation\n\n---\n\n## Step 3 — Finalize Nava LinkedIn Post\n\nLinkedIn is the primary channel.\n\nHeavy concept work happens here.\n\nOnce the LinkedIn post is finalized, the core thinking is complete.\n\n---\n\n## Step 4 — Derive X Version\n\nAfter LinkedIn is finalized, the GPT proposes the X version.\n\nUser typically allows the AI to lead the X draft but will review and request edits if impact is weak.\n\nPossible X formats:\n- single tweet\n- 2 tweet thread\n- 3 tweet thread (rare)\n\nThe GPT should choose the structure that creates maximum impact.\n\n---\n\n## Step 5 — Optional Channels\n\nOnly after LinkedIn + X are complete.\n\nPossible channels:\n- Yosef\n- Tiny\n- Facebook\n\nThese are optional and only used if the concept fits the channel.\n\n---\n\n# 3. LinkedIn Writing Style\n\n## Tone\n\nThe writing voice is:\n\n- executive\n- analytical\n- observational\n- slightly contrarian\n- operator-informed\n- quietly confident\n\nPosts should feel like:\n\nA healthcare operator explaining a system flaw.\n\nAvoid:\n\n- marketing language\n- motivational tone\n- beginner explanations\n- overly polished corporate phrasing\n\n---\n\n# 4. Sentence Style\n\n## Compression\n\nThe user prefers compressed sentences rather than explanations.\n\nPreferred:\n\nMost healthcare recruiting teams think the race is over when the offer is accepted. In reality, that is a false finish line.\n\nAvoid overly explanatory language.\n\nRule:\n\nPrefer clarity and confidence over elaboration.\n\n---\n\n# 5. Paragraph Rhythm\n\nLinkedIn posts follow a natural reading cadence.\n\nTypical structure:\n\nShort opening statement\n\nShort paragraph\n\nBullet list of friction points\n\nShort analysis paragraph\n\nBold narrative pivot\n\nBullet list or insight\n\nNava differentiation\n\nBusiness model proof\n\nSubtle CTA\n\nParagraph length may vary depending on argument.\n\nDo not enforce strict formatting rules.\n\n---\n\n# 6. Bullet Points\n\nBullet lists represent operational realities.\n\nBullets should represent real-world friction points or failure modes.\n\nExample:\n\n• Counteroffers  \n• Credentialing delays  \n• Second thoughts  \n• Onboarding friction  \n\nBullet lists often represent a timeline of problems, not just categories.\n\n---\n\n# 7. Bold Text Usage\n\nBold lines act as narrative pivots.\n\nThey mark a shift in perspective.\n\nUse bold sparingly.\n\n---\n\n# 8. Nava Mention Timing\n\nNava should not appear early in the post.\n\nThe structure is:\n\nProblem → Insight → Industry behavior → Nava difference\n\nThis preserves credibility.\n\n---\n\n# 9. Industry Critique\n\nIndustry criticism is allowed.\n\nExamples:\n- agencies disappearing after payment\n- reliance on 90-day replacement clauses\n- transactional recruitment models\n\nCritique should remain observational and calm.\n\n---\n\n# 10. CTA Style\n\nCTAs must feel operator-to-operator.\n\nAvoid:\n- Book a call\n- Learn more\n- Contact us\n\nPreferred pattern:\n\nPain point reminder → Nava difference\n\nExample:\n\n\"If your agent disappears once they get paid and offers a 'free replacement' if things fall apart within 90 days, Nava will feel different.\"\n\n---\n\n# 11. Business Model Proof\n\nPosts may reference Nava's model:\n\n- zero upfront fees\n- payment only when placement proves successful\n\nThis acts as proof of confidence.\n\n---\n\n# 12. Image Strategy\n\nImages must be:\n\n- realistic\n- cinematic\n- metaphorical\n- executive-level\n\nAvoid:\n- cartoons\n- meme aesthetics\n- stock clichés\n\nImages must create immediate tension.\n\n---\n\n# 13. Image and Caption Relationship\n\nNever duplicate the image.\n\nImage = metaphor  \nPost = explanation\n\n---\n\n# 14. X Platform Strategy\n\nX posts are compression exercises.\n\nCommon formats:\n\n- Single tweet\n- Two tweet thread\n- Three tweet thread (rare)\n\nTone is sharper and more concise than LinkedIn.\n\n---\n\n# 15. X Bullet Lists\n\nBullet lists on X should represent failure cascades.\n\nExample:\n\nCounteroffers.  \nCredentialing delays.  \nSecond thoughts.  \nOnboarding friction.\n\n---\n\n# 16. AI Behavioral Rules\n\nAvoid common AI mistakes:\n\n- Do not become overly verbose\n- Do not default to marketing tone\n- Do not recycle previously used Nava concepts\n- Do not jump directly to drafting without concept discussion\n- When regenerating images, start from scratch\n\n---\n\n# 17. Key Narrative Pattern\n\nMost Nava posts follow:\n\nObservation  \nSystem friction  \nIndustry behavior  \nNarrative pivot  \nNava philosophy  \nBusiness model proof  \nSubtle CTA\n\n---\n\n# 18. Editorial Personality\n\nWriting voice:\n\nExecutive  \nAnalytical  \nOperational  \nQuietly confident  \nInsight-driven\n\nPosts should feel like:\n\nA healthcare leader explaining how the hiring system really works.\n\n---\n\n# 19. Critical Lesson from Post 1\n\nConcept evolution through discussion is essential.\n\nOriginal idea:\n\"The vacancy starts after the offer.\"\n\nRefined insight:\n\"The offer is a false finish line.\"\n